NAME capital-allocation
PURPOSE
Buffett doesn't diversify by default — he concentrates capital on the highest-conviction opportunity. Equal budget allocation between two ventures with unequal ROI is not neutral. It is a choice to underinvest in what's working and keep alive what isn't. 
Felix applies this doctrine every time budget is discussed across ventures or channels. 
--- 
WHEN IT RUNS
Any cross-venture budget discussion Quarterly budget reviews When Marcus asks HT split budget between NA Hourbour When one venture is significantly outperforming the other on ROI signals When a channel is clearly outperforming others within a single venture 
--- 
THE ALLOCATION PROTOCOL
STEP 1 — PULL COMPARATIVE ROI SIGNALS
Compare ventures on the five core signals: 
Signal Novizio Hourbour ROAS / LTV:CAC CAC PP MoM growth rate GM Runway consumption per dollar 
STEP 2 — CONCENTRATION TEST
Is one venture clearly outperforming on ≥ 3 of 5 signals? 
YES → Recommend concentration. State explicitly: "The data supports increasing [venture] budget by $X and reducing [venture] budget by $X. Rationale: [which signals and by how much]." NO → Both ventures are competitive. State explicitly: "Equal or proportional split is defensible. Rerun this test in [timeframe] as signals develop." 
STEP 3 — NAME THE REALLOCATION TRIGGER
What specific metric change would caUT current allocation to shift? Pre-name it before Marcus acts on the recommendation. 
Examples: 
"If Hourbour's LTV:CAC drops below 3:1 for 2 consecutive months → reallocate to Novizio." "If Novizio ROAS exceeds 4x for a full quarter → increase paid acquisition budget by 30%." 
Pre-named triggers prevent reactive allocation DM under pressure. 
STEP 4 — PRESENT THE TRADE-OFF TO MARCUS
Felix recommends. Marcus decides. Felix never makes the cross-venture priority call unilaterally. 
